# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1910-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:1910-world-series/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1910-world-series/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1910-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1910-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1910-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1910-world-series/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1910-world-series/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1910-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1910-world-series/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1910-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1910-world-series/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1910-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1910-world-series/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The **1910 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1910 season.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The seventh edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff between the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The series was played from October 17 to 23, with the Athletics winning the series 4 games to 1, clinching the team's first World Series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Philadelphia-based team.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs of Philadelphia won three games and Eddie Collins supplied timely hitting.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Athletics were making their second appearance in the World Series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] They had lost the 1905 edition four games to one against the New York Giants.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] They had dominated the American League, leading it since early May, and eventually winning it by 14+1⁄2 games.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Their pitcher Jack Coombs led the American League in wins with a 31–9 record, and the Athletics had the lowest ERA in the league by some margin.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Chicago Cubs were a dominant team in the first decade of the 1900s.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] They had already won two World Series, and been runners-up in another; this was their fourth appearance.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The National League was initially closer than the American League, with the Cubs wrestling control of the division from the Pittsburgh Pirates in late May after a long winning streak.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] They never looked back, only increasing their lead over the course of the season.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Cubs' slugger Frank Schulte led the National League in home runs with 10, while pitcher King Cole had the lowest ERA in the league, 1.80.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Chicago Cubs won the division by 13 games.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Before the series, pundits were split over who the favorites were.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The pitching of the Athletics was generally held to be superior to that of the Cubs, as the Cubs pitchers were thought to be merely decent.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Cubs, however, were felt to have a stronger catcher in Johnny Kling, and slightly stronger batters as well.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Altogether, Philadelphia had a younger team, while Chicago had an older but experienced group of players.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Former coach Ned Hanlon picked the Athletics, as did former pitcher Jack Dunn.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] However, John McGraw, manager of the New York Giants, held that the Cubs would win the series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Before the series, the Athletics played the All-Stars, featuring Ty Cobb; they played poorly on the Friday before the Series, which lowered confidence in the ability of the Philadelphia team.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Second baseman Johnny Evers was out injured for the Cubs, while outfielder and strong batter Rube Oldring was injured for the Athletics.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] This World Series featured a new ball, manufactured by the Reach Company.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The ball was meant to be stronger and hold up better instead of becoming soft and losing its shape after being used for a long period of time.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Connie Mack chose Chief Bender to start game 1, while Orval Overall was selected by Frank Chance.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The second inning began with a double by Home Run Baker.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis sacrificed, and Danny Murphy singled to left to send Baker home.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Murphy then stole second and advanced to third on Jack Barry's sacrifice.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chief Bender, the pitcher, then came up to bat, and managed to bat in a run.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The next inning began with a Bris Lord double and a Eddie Collins sacrifice.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Home Run Baker hit a single to shortstop which allowed Lord to score, and the score was 0–3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] With two outs in the eighth inning, Eddie Collins was walked.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Collins was a leading base-stealer and McIntire attempted to get him out at first, but his throw to the first baseman was wild and Collins advanced to third.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Home Run Baker hit a double to right field and made it 0–4.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the ninth inning, a foul by Joe Tinker was fumbled by Athletics catcher Ira Thomas, and on the next pitch, Tinker hit a double.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Johnny Kling then doubled and Tinker scored.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Schulte was walked, and it seemed a comeback may be on, but Solly Hofman grounded out, ending the game at 1–4.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chief Bender allowed the Cubs just three hits and one unearned run.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Before the ninth inning, Bender had allowed only one hit and one base on balls.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] He also registered seven strikeouts, and, unusually for a pitcher, an RBI.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Baker had three hits and two RBI for the A's.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Star pitcher Jack Coombs was the starter for the Athletics, while Mordecai Brown began the game for the Cubs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Before the game, Ty Cobb and Nap Lajoie, winners of the Chalmers Awards, were presented with new cars from Chalmers Motor Company, though Lajoie was not present and a friend accepted the car in his stead.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs started the game shakily, walking Jimmy Sheckard, who was forced out at second after Frank Schulte grounded and got to first base.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Solly Hofman was also walked by Coombs, allowing Frank Chance to single and load the bases.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Heinie Zimmerman then hit a sacrifice to score one run for the Cubs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Coombs recovered somewhat and struck Harry Steinfeldt out, ending the inning with a score of 1–0.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the bottom of the third inning, Ira Thomas advanced to first after an error, and Amos Strunk and Bris Lord had base hits, though Strunk was forced out at second base.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Eddie Collins hit a double, allowing Thomas and Lord to reach home and make the score 1–2.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Although Coombs continued to struggle, and twice fumbled the ball in the fifth inning, good fielding allowed Philadelphia to keep Chicago at one run.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis singled to left in the bottom of the fifth, allowing Eddie Collins to score from second base, increasing the Athletics' lead to 1–3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the seventh inning, the Cubs got one back after Jimmy Sheckard doubled and Frank Chance hit hard to center.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Coombs additionally walked Solly Hofman for the third time, and the game no longer looked as though it was firmly in Philadelphia's hands.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The bottom of the seventh began with Eddie Collins being walked, and Home Run Baker singled, putting Collins on third.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Then Harry Davis and Danny Murphy doubled, bringing home three runs in Collins, Baker, and Davis himself.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Murphy went to third after Jack Barry sacrificed, Ira Thomas sent Murphy home.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Bris Lord hit a fly-out, but Jimmy Sheckard dropped the ball, and Strunk came home.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Lord finally ended the inning when he was caught stealing second.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The six-run rally left the score at 2–9.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] After the inning, Lew Richie came in for the struggling Mordecai Brown.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Heinie Zimmerman hit a double in the ninth inning, allowing Solly Hofman to score.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The game ended 3–9, giving the Athletics a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The two teams left by train for Chicago that evening, in preparation for game three on Thursday.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs had pitched erratically, allowing eight hits and walking nine, but still picked up the win.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Cubs left 14 men on base, a Series record at that time.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The A's combed Mordecai Brown for 13 hits.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Eddie Collins was praised for his performance, which involved getting 3 hits out of four at-bats, scoring two runs and batting in another.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs started again for Philadelphia, while Ed Reulbach was Chicago's starter.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The game was played on a cold, cloudy day, and it drizzled during the second half of the match.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] An attendance of at least 30,000 fans had been expected by Chicago officials, but only 26,210 people showed up, though those who did stayed almost the entire game in spite of the home team's struggles.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The game got off to an exciting and even start.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The first batter, Amos Strunk of the Athletics, was walked by starting pitcher Ed Reulbach.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Bris Lord sacrificed, and Home Run Baker singled on a low curveball, putting the Athletics up 1–0.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] However, in Chicago's half of the inning, they matched the Athletics, as Solly Hofman sent Jimmy Sheckard home after Sheckard had advanced to third on Frank Schulte's double.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis scored for Philadelphia at the beginning of the second inning on a Jack Barry double, and Barry himself scored when pitcher Jack Coombs doubled once more.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago quickly matched this as well – Joe Tinker doubled, and Ginger Beaumont and Jimmy Sheckard walked, loading the bases.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Schulte doubled again to tie the game at 3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Before the third inning, Reulbach was taken off, and Harry McIntire assumed his spot on the pitcher's mound for the Cubs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] With one out and Eddie Collins on first, Home Run Baker hit a triple and put Philadelphia back in the lead.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis was hit by a pitch and went to first, and then Danny Murphy hit a three-run home run to right.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] This caused controversy as the Chicago players protested that the ball had not gone far enough and the hit should have counted as a double.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago's player-manager Frank Chance was ejected from the game, the second time in World Series history that a manager was punished in this way.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] McIntire was then taken off and replaced with Jack Pfiester.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] However, Pfiester's first pitch was hit for a double by Jack Barry, who scored when Ira Thomas hit to shortstop Joe Tinker.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Tinker threw poorly to first base, allowing the Athletics to score their fifth run of the inning.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] A double play finally stemmed the bleeding, but the inning ended 8–3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] After this, Coombs settled into the form that had gained him a reputation as one of the best pitchers in the league.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] His breaking balls were unhittable, and Chicago were unable to get back into the game.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The next few innings therefore passed uneventfully in the batting department, until the seventh inning.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The inning started with two outs, and Harry Steinfeldt had the chance to finish it, but he fumbled Home Run Baker's hit and the Philadelphia player got to first.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The bases were filled by Harry Davis and Danny Murphy, and Jack Barry hit his third double of the game to earn the Athletics two runs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The bases were loaded again when Ira Thomas was walked.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs then hit a single to score two more runs, giving the pitcher three RBI, and making the score 12–3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago scored twice in the eighth inning as a result of a passed ball.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] After Chicago's implosion, blame was assigned to the pitchers, who The Washington Times described as "absolute failures".
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Chance even acknowledged that "Our pitchers haven't been able to stop the Philadelphia hitters." On the other side of the coin, the Athletics looked unstoppable.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Ty Cobb predicted that they would sweep the series, and Connie Mack confidently pronounced that they would defeat the Cubs in game 4.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Athletics rapped out 16 hits to Chicago's 7.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs gave up 5 runs but won his second game of the series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chief Bender was chosen to start for Philadelphia, while King Cole was put out for Chicago as the last hope for the Cubs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Additionally, Jimmy Archer started as Chicago's catcher instead of Johnny Kling, as the Cubs believed that the Athletics had figured out Kling's signs.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The game was planned to be held on Friday, but was postponed due to rain.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago began the scoring in the bottom of the first.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jimmy Sheckard was walked and stole second, before being brought home by Solly Hofman.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] However, in the third inning, with two outs, Amos Strunk tripled and Chief Bender, who was on first having been walked, scored.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Strunk accidentally slid past third base and was tagged out, but Bender was home before him, tying the game at 1.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the fourth inning, Philadelphia had Eddie Collins on first when Home Run Baker doubled.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis struck out, but Danny Murphy doubled again and scored two runs for the Athletics.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the Cubs' half of the inning, Frank Schulte got to third after Solly Hofman's double.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Chance singled and Schulte went home, making it 3–2.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago had a good chance to re-tie the game, as there were no outs and they had men on first and second, but the Athletics took out Hofman and Heinie Zimmerman on a double play, and Harry Steinfeldt hit a fly ball, ending the fourth.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The next few innings passed with many close chances for the Athletics.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In both the sixth and the eighth inning Home Run Baker was out at the plate.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Chicago pinch hit Johnny Kling for King Cole in their half of the eighth inning, and put Mordecai Brown on the mound for the ninth.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the bottom of the ninth, the Cubs were still behind 3–2, in serious danger of being swept.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Frank Schulte doubled, and got to third when Hofman was tagged out bunting.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Player-manager Frank Chance came up to bat with one out, and was hit by the first pitch on the finger, but the umpire ruled that he had walked into it.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Then he tripled to center, tying the game.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Although they now had a man on third, the next two Chicago players hit fly outs, and the game went into extra innings.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the bottom of the tenth inning, with two outs, Jimmy Sheckard came up to bat.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jimmy Archer was on second, having doubled.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Sheckard's single to center won the game for Chicago, 4–3.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs started Game 5 for the Athletics, while Mordecai Brown was tasked with keeping the Cubs in contention.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Further, Philadelphia manager Connie Mack opted to start Topsy Hartsel in left field, moving Bris Lord to center rather than Amos Strunk, and also switched catcher Ira Thomas with Jack Lapp.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The game was played on a bright, sunny Sunday.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Topsy Hartsel began the game with a single and stole second while Bris Lord struck out.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] He scored after Eddie Collins hit a single to center.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Philadelphia kept this 1–0 lead until the bottom of the second, when Frank Chance doubled.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] He made it to third base when Heinie Zimmerman bunted, and scored a tying run on Harry Steinfeldt's hit.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Cubs had another chance to score with the bases loaded and one out in the fourth inning, but Coombs struck out two straight Cubs batters.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Athletics capitalized on this, with Jack Lapp's fifth inning single allowing Danny Murphy to score from second base.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The score was still 2–1 when the eighth inning began.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] With one out, Topsy Hartsel stole second, and was controversially called safe.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Bris Lord doubled to right, giving the Athletics a run.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Lord scored in turn after Eddie Collins doubled.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Collins stole third and Home Run Baker singled, but the Cubs defense opted to force Collins out at the plate, allowing Baker to get to first.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Harry Davis was walked – Mordecai Brown's first base on balls in Game 5 – and Danny Murphy tripled.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] His hit had blown past Heinie Zimmerman to center fielder Solly Hofman, scoring Baker, but Hofman's poor throw home allowed Davis to score as well.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] The Cubs scored a run in the bottom of the eighth when Frank Chance singled to send Jimmy Sheckard home.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] In the ninth inning, Harry Steinfeldt and Joe Tinker flew out.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jimmy Archer singled, and Johnny Kling emerged to pinch hit for the pitcher, as he did in Game 4.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Kling grounded to shortstop Jack Barry, who ran to second base to force Archer out.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Jack Coombs became the third pitcher in World Series history to win 3 games without a loss.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] Babe Adams did it the year before, but in seven games, and Christy Mathewson accomplished the feat in the 1905 Series.
[src:1910-world-series/1910-world-series] This was the Athletics' first World Series title.
